data.content:
Yes — MSTest 3.4+ supports **tuples** with `[DynamicData]`, eliminating the `object[]` indirection:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:** The data source returns `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` instead of `IEnumerable<object[]>`. Tuple element types are checked at compile time, so a mismatched type (e.g., accidentally passing an `int` where `string` is expected) becomes a compiler error instead of a runtime failure.

The test method signature stays the same — MSTest destructures the tuple into the method parameters automatically.
